  "text": "This analysis identifies all production Go source files that configure or define DialTimeout across the Kubernetes and etcd ecosystems.\n\n## Kubernetes API Server (kubernetes/kubernetes)\n\nThe Kubernetes API server uses etcd3 as its backend storage. DialTimeout configuration is found in two critical files:\n\n1. **staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/storagebackend/factory/etcd3.go** - This file contains the main etcd3 client factory. It defines a constant `dialTimeout = 20 * time.Second` (line 69) with a comment explaining that it was set to 20 seconds to prevent TLS connection failures on heavily loaded ARM64 CPUs (issue #64649). This timeout is used in the `newETCD3Client` function (line 286) when creating the clientv3.Config object, setting the `DialTimeout` field to the `dialTimeout` constant value (line 347).\n\n2. **staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/etcd3/preflight/checks.go** - This file performs preflight checks on etcd connectivity. It defines a `connectionTimeout = 1 * time.Second` constant and uses Go's `net.DialTimeout` function (line 39) to test reachability of etcd servers.\n\n## etcd-io/etcd Client (client/)\n\nThe etcd client library defines and uses DialTimeout across multiple files:\n\n1. **client/v3/config.go** - Defines the `Config` struct (line 26) with the `DialTimeout` field (line 35) described as \"the timeout for failing to establish a connection\". This is a core configuration parameter for all etcd v3 clients.\n\n2. **client/v3/client.go** - The client implementation uses `DialTimeout` in multiple places:\n   - In the `newClient` function to create a timeout context for dial operations (lines 312-314)\n   - In authentication token retrieval (lines 447-449)\n   - In endpoint synchronization (lines 492-495)\n\n3. **client/v3/doc.go** - Contains package documentation with examples showing DialTimeout usage (lines 22, 37).\n\n4. **client/v3/lease.go** - Uses `DialTimeout` when creating lease clients, adding 1 second to the configured timeout (line 192).\n\n5. **client/v3/maintenance.go** - Uses `DialTimeout` when authenticating with the server (lines 89-91).\n\n## etcd-io/etcd Server (server/)\n\nThe etcd server configures dial timeouts for both peer-to-peer communication and client proxy scenarios:\n\n1. **server/config/config.go** - Defines the `ServerConfig` struct and the `PeerDialTimeout()` method (line 321) which calculates the peer dial timeout as \"1s for queue wait and election timeout\" plus the election timeout duration.\n\n2. **server/etcdmain/config.go** - Defines the `configProxy` struct with `ProxyDialTimeoutMs` field (line 70) with a default value of 1000 milliseconds (line 105). This is parsed from command-line flags (line 218) with the flag `--proxy-dial-timeout`.\n\n3. **server/etcdmain/etcd.go** - Uses `ProxyDialTimeoutMs` to configure HTTP proxy client timeouts (lines 256, 270) by converting milliseconds to duration.\n\n4. **server/etcdmain/grpc_proxy.go** - Sets `DialTimeout: 5 * time.Second` explicitly in the client configuration when creating proxy clients (lines 338, 356).\n\n5. **server/etcdserver/api/rafthttp/transport.go** - Defines the `Transport` struct with a `DialTimeout` field (line 100) described as \"maximum duration before timing out dial of the request\". The `Start()` method (line 133) uses this timeout when creating stream and pipeline round trippers (lines 135, 139).\n\n6. **server/etcdserver/server.go** - In the `NewServer` function, creates the raft HTTP transport and passes `cfg.PeerDialTimeout()` as the DialTimeout value (line 689).\n\n## Configuration Chain\n\nThe configuration chain follows this flow:\n1. Command-line flags or config files set timeout values\n2. `ServerConfig.PeerDialTimeout()` calculates peer timeouts based on election parameters\n3. The etcd server initializes `Transport` with the calculated `PeerDialTimeout()`\n4. The Kubernetes API server independently sets `dialTimeout = 20 seconds` for its etcd client connections\n5. Both the etcd server proxy and Kubernetes use the etcd v3 client library which reads the `Config.DialTimeout` field during connection establishment\n"
}

